    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <h3>Is Cursor better than Windsurf?</h3>
    <p>Cursor is better for developers who want the most polished, feature-rich AI IDE with the fastest autocomplete, the most mature multi-file Composer, and the largest community. Windsurf is better for developers who want a streamlined AI experience with Cascade's flow-based interaction, stronger debugging context, and a lower price. Neither is universally better — it depends on whether you prioritize ecosystem maturity or a cleaner, more affordable AI workflow.</p>
    <h3>Is Windsurf better than Cursor for beginners?</h3>
    <p>Yes, Windsurf is generally better for beginners. Its interface is cleaner and less cluttered than Cursor's, the Cascade flow is more intuitive than Cursor's chat-based approach, and the free tier with unlimited basic autocomplete lets new developers explore without worrying about usage limits. Windsurf's gentler learning curve makes it easier to start with AI-native coding, while Cursor's denser UI and more advanced Composer suit experienced power users.</p>
    <h3>Which AI coding assistant should developers choose in 2026?</h3>
    <p>In 2026, choose Cursor if you want the most complete AI IDE with the fastest autocomplete and largest ecosystem. Choose Windsurf if you want Cascade's flow-based AI interaction, better pricing ($15/month vs $20/month), and a cleaner interface. Both are excellent AI coding assistants — the right choice depends on your budget, preferred workflow, and whether you value ecosystem maturity or innovative AI interaction design.</p>
    <h3>Can Cursor and Windsurf replace traditional coding workflows?</h3>
    <p>Yes, both Cursor and Windsurf can replace traditional coding workflows for many developers. Their multi-file editing, codebase-aware AI, and natural language code generation handle tasks that used to require manual typing, searching, and refactoring. However, developers still need to review AI-generated code, understand architecture decisions, and manage complex debugging. Most teams in 2026 use these AI IDEs alongside traditional review and testing practices rather than as a full replacement for engineering judgment.</p>
